  "prompt": "Are there legal frameworks in place to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are comprehensive legal frameworks in place globally to combat money laundering. These frameworks are established at both international and national levels to prevent, detect, and prosecute money laundering activities. Key components include:\n\n### **International Frameworks:**\n1. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF):**\n   - The FATF is an intergovernmental organization that sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT). Its **40 Recommendations** provide a framework for countries to implement effective AML/CFT measures.\n\n2. **United Nations Conventions:**\n   - The **UN Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)** and the **UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)** include provisions to combat money laundering.\n\n3. **European Union Directives:**\n   - The EU has issued several **Anti-Money Laundering Directives** (AMLD) that require member states to implement AML measures, such as customer due diligence, reporting suspicious transactions, and establishing financial intelligence units (FIUs).\n\n### **National Frameworks:**\n1. **Legislation:**\n   - Most countries have enacted specific laws to combat money laundering. Examples include:\n     - **USA:** The **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Patriot Act**.\n     - **UK:** The **Proceeds of Crime Act 2002** and the **Money Laundering Regulations**.\n     - **India:** The **Prevention of Money Laundering Act (PMLA), 2002**.\n\n2. **Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs):**\n   - Many countries have established FIUs to collect, analyze, and disseminate information related to suspicious financial activities.\n\n3. **Regulatory Bodies:**\n   - Regulatory authorities, such as central banks, securities and exchange commissions, and financial regulatory agencies, enforce AML compliance in their respective sectors.\n\n4. **Reporting Requirements:**\n   - Financial institutions and other regulated entities are required to report suspicious transactions, maintain records, and conduct customer due diligence (CDD) and enhanced due diligence (EDD) for high-risk customers.\n\n### **Key Measures:**\n",
